glands in either control, Dp110-, Akt-, or RasV12-expressing salivary glands (Figures 4A‚Äì4C and data not shown). DNA fragmentation was detected by TUNEL in the Dp110-, Akt-, and RasV12-expressing glands 13.5 hr apf (Figures 4E and 4F and data not shown). Dp110-expressing salivary glands are also positively stained with an antibody to cleaved caspase-3 and show decreased nuclear lamin staining at 13.5 hr apf (Figure 4H). Further, we detected caspase-3 activity by cleavage of the substrate DEVD-AMC at 13.5 hr apf in Canton-S and Dp110-, Akt-, and RasV12-expressing glands, but not in p35-expressing glands (Figure 4I). Together, these data indicate that caspases are active and capable of substrate cleavage in the presence of PI3K activity in salivary glands. We further tested the role of caspases in autophagic cell death by analyzing salivary gland cell death in caspase loss-of-function mutants. We previously showed that salivary glands are partially degraded when caspases are inhibited by p35 expression and are completely degraded in loss-of-function mutants in the effector caspase drice (Muro et al., 2006). Similarly, salivary glands are predominantly if not completely degraded in loss-of-function mutants in either the Apaf-1 ortholog ark or in the initiator caspase dronc that develop normally (Figures 5A, 5B, and S3E). We do observe a small percentage of ark and dronc mutant pupae that have salivary glands or partially de-

graded salivary glands, but in all cases these animals also possess defects indicative of a developmental arrest prior to the onset of normal salivary gland destruction (Figures S3A and S3B). To circumvent the developmental defects associated with global loss-of-caspase function, we selectively knocked down ark and dronc in salivary glands using RNAi. Leulier et al. used a GFP reporter to show that salivary gland degradation is delayed in pupae expressing ark-IR and dronc-IR in salivary glands (Leulier et al., 2006), and we conÔ¨Årmed by histology that glands are predominantly if not completely degraded in these animals (Figures S3C‚ÄìS3E). Finally, similar to p35, DIAP1expressing salivary glands are partly degraded (S. Dutta and E.H.B., unpublished data). As salivary glands are partially degraded when caspases are inhibited, additional caspase-independent factors must be required for type II autophagic cell death of salivary glands. Since we detect caspase activity in Dp110-expressing glands, we tested whether combining PI3K-dependent growth with caspase inhibition would lead to an increased inhibition of salivary gland degradation. When Dp110 is either combined with p35 or expressed in dronc mutants, the persistence of salivary glands with intact lumen is signiÔ¨Åcantly increased compared to either expression of Dp110 or p35, or in dronc mutants alone (Figures 5C‚Äì 5F). These data indicate that it is the combined inÔ¨Çuences

